Q1: WWE Universal Championship

(a).

WWE <- c(1, 188, 28, 504, 64, 156, 98, 28, 81, 119, 27.5, 150.5, 7, 757)
# Exponential
1 / mean(WWE)
## [1] 0.006337709

For the Exponential, MLE of \(\lambda\) is \(\hat{\lambda} \approx 0.00634\).

(b).

# Gamma
x.bar <- mean(WWE)
sigma2.hat <- mean(WWE^2) - x.bar^2
# Fit a gamma
gamma.nll <- function(pars, data){
  k <- pars[1]
  lambda <- pars[2]
  lik <- dgamma(data, k, lambda)
  return(-sum(log(lik)))
}
k.mom <- x.bar^2 / sigma2.hat
lambda.mom <- x.bar / sigma2.hat
gamma.mle <- optim(par = c(k.mom, lambda.mom), fn = gamma.nll, data = WWE, hessian = TRUE)
## Warning in dgamma(data, k, lambda): NaNs produced

## Warning in dgamma(data, k, lambda): NaNs produced

## Warning in dgamma(data, k, lambda): NaNs produced

## Warning in dgamma(data, k, lambda): NaNs produced
gamma.mle$par
## [1] 0.662793943 0.004200934
sqrt(diag(solve(gamma.mle$hessian)))
## [1] 0.204397082 0.001741776

For the gamma, I got \(\hat{k} = 0.663\) and \(\hat{\lambda} = 0.0042\), with standard errors of \(0.204\) and \(0.0017\) respectively.

(c). Wald test for H0 : k = 1

gamma.var <- solve(gamma.mle$hessian)
w <- (gamma.mle$par[1] - 1)^2 / gamma.var[1, 1]
w
## [1] 2.721707
1 - pchisq(w, df = 1)
## [1] 0.09899211

The Wald test gives a \(P\)-value about 0.099. There is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis at the level 0.1. Therefore, we cannot conclude that the data does not follow an Exponential distribution.

(d). LR test for H0 : k = 1

# LL: gamma
llg <- -gamma.nll(gamma.mle$par, data = WWE)
llg
## [1] -83.93121
# or
llg_2 <- -gamma.mle$value
llg_2
## [1] -83.93121
# LL: expo
lle <- sum(log(dexp(WWE, 1/mean(WWE))))
lle
## [1] -84.85733
# LR test stat
LR <- 2*(llg - lle)
1 - pchisq(LR, df = 1)
## [1] 0.1735236

A likelihood ratio test gives a \(P\)-value of about 0.17. There isnt enough evidence to reject the Exponential hypothesis.

(e).

# AIC: gamma
2*gamma.mle$value + 2*2
## [1] 171.8624
# AIC: expo
-2*sum(log(dexp(WWE, 1/mean(WWE)))) + 2*1
## [1] 171.7147

AICs are very close, indicating these two models have about the same performance. Exponential model has slightly lower AIC, and therefore is fitting the data a bit better.

Q2: Florida crime

(a).

FloridaCrime <- read.table("FloridaCrime.txt", header = TRUE)
crime.lmA <- lm(Crime ~ HS, data = FloridaCrime)
crime.lmA
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Crime ~ HS, data = FloridaCrime)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)           HS  
##     -50.857        1.486

The equation can be written as

\[ \textrm{Crimes per 1000 residents} = -50.86 + 1.486 \times \textrm{percent with high school education} + \textrm{error} \]

or \[ \textrm{Predicted crime rate} = -50.86 + 1.486 \times \textrm{percent with high school education} \] (b).

crime.lmB <- lm(Crime ~ HS + Urban, data = FloridaCrime)
crime.lmB
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Crime ~ HS + Urban, data = FloridaCrime)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)           HS        Urban  
##     59.1181      -0.5834       0.6825

The regression equation is \[ \textrm{Predicted crime rate} = 59.11 - 0.583 \times \textrm{percent with high school education} + 0.683 \times \textrm{urban percentage} \] or \[ \textrm{Crimes per 1000 residents} = 59.11 - 0.583 \times \textrm{percent with high school education} + 0.683 \times \textrm{urban percentage} + \textrm{error} \]

(c). The easiest way to quantitatively compare the models is by using AIC:

AIC(crime.lmA)
## [1] 626.0932
AIC(crime.lmB)
## [1] 601.8526

The model with both high school and urban percentages has a clearly lower AIC, so we would guess it would be better for predictive purposes. (Alternatively you could split data into training and test set and compare the MSEs.)

(c). The positive coefficient for high school in (a) means counties with more high school education tend to have higher crime rates. The effect is statisticallt significant.

summary(crime.lmA)

We can also see this clearly from a scatterplot:

ggplot(FloridaCrime, aes(x = HS, y = Crime)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + ggtitle("Crime rates in Florida counties")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

However, the coefficient for high school becomes negative in the model for (b). Roughly, this means that for counties with the same urban percentage, counties with more high school education will have lower predicted crime rates (though the effect is not statistically significant.)

summary(crime.lmB)
##

If you look more closely at the data (which for this exercise you were not required to), youll find that the effect is driven mostly by counties that are very highly urban. In particular, Dade County (where Miami is) is 98.8% urban and has the highest crime rate in Florida, while being below average in high school education.

FloridaCrime |> filter(Urban > 85) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = HS, y = Crime, label = County)) + geom_label() + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + ggtitle("Crime rates in Florida counties that are at least 85% urban")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

One possible explanation (though not the only possible one) for all this is that urban percentage is the far more important determinant of crime rates urban areas have more opportunities for (reportable) crimes than rural areas. In comparison, perhaps education doesnt matter as much.

Q3: Biochemists

(a). The MLE for \(\lambda\) is just the sample mean.

biochemists <- read.table("biochemists.txt", header = TRUE)
lambda.hat <- mean(biochemists$art)
lambda.hat
## [1] 1.692896

So we can model the number of articles as having a Poisson distribution with parameter \(\lambda = 1.69\).

(b). We can copy-paste the pois0.nll() function from earlier in the course.

pois0.nll <- function(pars, data){
  p <- pars[1]
  lambda <- pars[2]
  pois.lik <- dpois(data, lambda)
  real.lik <- rep(NA, length(data))
  which0 <- (data == 0)
  real.lik[which0 == FALSE] <- (1 - p) * pois.lik[which0 == FALSE]
  real.lik[which0 == TRUE] <- p + (1 - p) * pois.lik[which0 == TRUE]
  loglik <- log(real.lik)
  return(-sum(loglik))
}

Now apply it to biochemists$art:

art.zip <- optim(par = c(mean(biochemists$art == 0), mean(biochemists$art)), fn = pois0.nll, data = biochemists$art)
art.zip$par
## [1] 0.2066511 2.1339491

I get MLEs of \(\hat{p} = 0.207\) and \(\hat{\lambda} = 2.13\).

We can compare the models using AIC:

# Poisson model
pois.ll <- sum(log(dpois(biochemists$art, lambda.hat)))
-2 * pois.ll + 2 * 1
## [1] 3487.147
# ZIP model
2 * art.zip$value + 2 * 2
## [1] 3362.782

The zero-inflated model has the lower AIC (and doesnt have implausible parameter estimates), so its better by that criterion.

Alternatively, you could simulate from the Poisson and zero-inflated Poisson models, and verify that the zero-inflated model gives results that look more like the raw data.

set.seed(352)
pois.sim <- rpois(915, lambda.hat)
zip.sim <- rpois(915, art.zip$par[2])
zeroes <- rbinom(915, 1, art.zip$par[1])
zip.sim <- (1 - zeroes) * zip.sim
par(mfrow = c(1, 3))
hist(pois.sim, breaks = seq(-0.5, 19.5, 1), main = "Simulated Poisson")
hist(zip.sim, breaks = seq(-0.5, 19.5, 1), main = "Simulated zero-inflated Poisson")
hist(biochemists$art, breaks = seq(-0.5, 19.5, 1), main = "Observed data")

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

Neither of the models is perfect both fail to capture that there are some extreme cases where somehow people manage to produce ten or more articles in three years. However, at least the zero-inflated model correctly captures that more than a quarter of the students produced no articles at all.

(c).

nokid <- subset(biochemists, kid5 == 0)
nokid.zip <- optim(par = c(mean(nokid$art == 0), mean(nokid$art)), fn = pois0.nll, data = nokid$art, hessian = TRUE)
nokid.zip$par
## [1] 0.1958819 2.1405415
sqrt(diag(solve(nokid.zip$hessian)))
## [1] 0.02265433 0.07885619
kid <- subset(biochemists, kid5 > 0)
kid.zip <- optim(par = c(mean(kid$art == 0), mean(kid$art)), fn = pois0.nll, data = kid$art, hessian = TRUE)
kid.zip$par
## [1] 0.2268417 2.1199106
sqrt(diag(solve(kid.zip$hessian)))
## [1] 0.03200907 0.11047270

For students with no children 5 or younger, the ZIP has MLEs \(\hat{p} = 0.196\) and \(\hat{\lambda} = 2.14\). For students with at least one child 5 or younger, the ZIP has MLEs \(\hat{p} = 0.226\) and \(\hat{\lambda} = 2.12\). If we take this literally, it implies that having a child 5 or younger increases your probability of producing zero articles, and even if you do produce something, it very slightly reduces the number of articles you produce. However, the differences between the models are not too big compared to the standard errors, so we shouldnt be too certain about this.

Q4: Crabs

(a).

crabs <- read.table("crabs.txt", header = TRUE)
crabs.lmA <- lm(SpermTotal ~ Mass, data = crabs)
crabs.lmA
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SpermTotal ~ Mass, data = crabs)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)         Mass  
##    16.79024      0.00319
AIC(crabs.lmA)
## [1] 997.3144

The regression equation is \[ \textrm{SpermTotal} = 16.79 + 0.00319 \times \textrm{Mass} + \textrm{error} \]

with AIC 997.3.

(b).

crabs.lmB <- lm(SpermTotal ~ Mass + Location, data = crabs)
crabs.lmB
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SpermTotal ~ Mass + Location, data = crabs)
## 
## Coefficients:
##       (Intercept)               Mass   LocationDelaware      LocationMaine  
##         18.597190           0.001035           1.301277          -1.916908  
##    LocationSapelo        LocationSHK  LocationWellfleet  
##          0.974363          -0.412806          -1.275529

The regression equation is \[ \textrm{SpermTotal} = 18.6 + 0.00104 \times \textrm{Mass} + 1.31 (\textrm{Delaware}) - 1.92 (\textrm{Maine}) + 0.97 (\textrm{Sapelo}) - 0.41 (\textrm{SHK}) - 1.28 (\textrm{Wellfleet}) + \textrm{error} \]

where the location terms are added if and only if the crab comes from that location.

AIC(crabs.lmB)
## [1] 945.5006

The AIC is 945.5, less than for model (a).

(c).

crabs.lmC <- lm(SpermTotal ~ Mass + Location + Mass:Location, data = crabs)

Here are the regression coefficients of the interaction model (theres no point writing them all out manually):

crabs.lmC
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SpermTotal ~ Mass + Location + Mass:Location, data = crabs)
## 
## Coefficients:
##            (Intercept)                    Mass        LocationDelaware  
##              16.334833                0.003743                5.444406  
##          LocationMaine          LocationSapelo             LocationSHK  
##               1.028798                1.655901                1.225441  
##      LocationWellfleet   Mass:LocationDelaware      Mass:LocationMaine  
##               1.795535               -0.004557               -0.004472  
##    Mass:LocationSapelo        Mass:LocationSHK  Mass:LocationWellfleet  
##              -0.001616               -0.001504               -0.003865
AIC(crabs.lmC)
## [1] 944.9238

The AIC is 944.9, very slightly lower than the model in (b).

(d).

BIC(crabs.lmA)
## [1] 1007.973
BIC(crabs.lmB)
## [1] 973.9243
BIC(crabs.lmC)
## [1] 991.1122

Which model is best? I think you could choose either (b) or (c). (c) has the lowest AIC, but only by a bit, and it might be overfitting. (b) has a decent AIC, and the lowest BIC, and makes sense.

(e).

ints <- coef(crabs.lmC)[1] + c(0, coef(crabs.lmC)[3:7])
slopes <- coef(crabs.lmC)[2] + c(0, coef(crabs.lmC)[8:12])
colors <- c("grey", "orange", "skyblue", "turquoise", "yellow", "blue")

# use basic plot function

plot(crabs$Mass, crabs$SpermTotal, pch = ".",
     xlab = "Mass", 
     ylab = "SpermTotal",
  main = "Regression lines for crab sperm by location")
abline(ints[1], slopes[1], col = colors[1])
abline(ints[2], slopes[2], col = colors[2])
abline(ints[3], slopes[3], col = colors[3])
abline(ints[4], slopes[4], col = colors[4])
abline(ints[5], slopes[5], col = colors[5])
abline(ints[6], slopes[6], col = colors[6])

# use ggplot

ggplot(crabs, aes(x = Mass, y = SpermTotal, color = Location)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_abline(intercept = ints, slope = slopes, color = colors, linewidth = 1.5) +
  ggtitle("Regression lines for crab sperm by location") +
  labs(color = "Legend") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = colors)

Does this look questionable? I dont know. It seems a bit weird that the lines for Delaware and Maine clearly go down I wouldve though that larger crabs would have higher sperm counts regardless of location. But then Im not very knowledgeable about crab reproduction.

Q5: Fall 2024 Midterm 2 Exam Question

  1. Exponential model is better as it has a lower AIC, 836.1503 vs 837.5869.

  2. W = 0.5893562. p-value: 0.4426682. Fail to reject H0.

  3. LR test stat: 0.5633861. p-value: 0.4528991. Fail to reject H0.
